post_text:
Hello Jacobson Distance-Learning Families,

Just a Reminder:

The first couple of weeks of in-person school will focus heavily on building relationships, making connections, and learning or remembering how to "do school." This is especially important for our primary learners as school is still very new to them. At this time, distance learning lessons will be different. Distance learners (DLs) will not need those same skills but will need e-learning skills. Full distance learning lessons will launch (six digital lessons per day) starting on Sept. 17th. This also allows time for DLs to get their devices if they have not and troubleshoot their technology. DLs will also be contacted by their teacher regarding other items they may need to pick up, such as math book consumables and handwriting paper for younger students.

Lots of flexibility will be allowed as we all, school and families, settle into this new normal.

You should hear from your teacher by Wednesday at the latest. Feel free to join the morning getting-started zoom with Mrs. Kurvers!

Please, welcome our new early childhood and Tiger Care paraprofessional, Miss Kost!

"Hello everyone! My name is Anika Kost and I am so incredibly excited to be the new Tiger Care Program Coordinator and Early Childhood paraprofessional. I am currently enrolled at Pine Technical and Community College in the Early Childhood Program and just recently worked in the School Age Care Program in Forest Lake. I am so thankful to be working in Rush City where I went to elementary school and also where a lot of my family grew up and went to school. In my free time I enjoy going up to the North Shore and spending time with my boyfriend and my many family members! I can’t wait for this school year!"

Welcome to Rush, Miss Kost!

We are excited to introduce our final Dept. 56 Team Member - Mrs. Strehlow!

"Hi! My name is Rachel Strehlow, and I am excited to be teaching 5th Grade Math this year. I am going into my 10th year of teaching. For the last 9 years, I have taught 4th grade for five and done a variety of other roles including enrichment teacher and math intervention teacher. My husband and I live in Forest Lake with our two boys. In my free time, I enjoy spending time with my family, going on walks, running, hunting, fishing, reading,and playing my flute. I look forward to a fun year of learning!"

Mrs. Strehlow will be an incredible asset to 5th grade, welcome!

Tigers Football Fall Training Sessions

We have some dates finalized for Tigers fall football training sessions. We will be meeting on Tuesdays and Thursdays. The dates will be Sept 15, 17, 22, 24, 29, and Oct. 1st. The training sessions will be held right after school from 3:15-5:30. Any questions about these training sessions can be sent to Coach Lattimore or Coach O'Donnell.
In order to participate in the training sessions during the fall, students will need to be registered through the school district and have a current physical on file in the activities office. Registration is the same process as during a regular year. Here is the link: https://rushcity-ar.rschooltoday.com/ If you have any questions or troubles registering, please contact. Mr. Rood, our Activities Director.

post_text: Please help us welcome Mari Ringness to the school counselor position at RCHS this year. Mari originally grew up in Anoka, but has lived in Pine City the past 25 years. Mari has two adult kids (her son recently graduated from U of MN Duluth and her daughter is attending LSC). Mari attended UW-Stout for her undergrad and Concordia University Wisconsin for her master's degree in school counseling. Mari enjoys being outdoors and likes biking, kayaking, boating, swimming, golfing, hiking, cross country skiing and snowshoeing in the winter. She loves living in a small town and drives her blue scooter whenever possible around town. Mari is thrilled to join us at RCHS and looks forward to meeting everyone!

Please join us in welcoming Sheila Shykes to the Rush City High School Teaching Staff. She will be teaching our 7th and 10th grade English classes. Sheila is originally from Coon Rapids, Minnesota but moved to Cambridge when she was in high school. She currently resides in Princeton, MN. After high school Sheila attended Viterbo University in La Crosse, WI where she earned a double major in Secondary Education and English. Sheila and her family love anything that involves the outdoors: Camping, Fishing, Traveling, etc. Here is a fun picture of your and her beautiful family.

Welcome Sheila!

Mr. Engel is originally from Rush City and he graduated from RCHS in 2013. He attended Anoka-Ramsey Community College and transferred to St. Cloud State University where he graduated in 2017. He loves the outdoors, running, and road tripping through Minnesota. He is also a huge fan of coffee, reading, and playing board games with friends and family. Attached is a picture of him with his father at the Polar Plunge 5k this past March!

Are you behind credits for graduation? Rush City High School is offering Credit Recovery this summer! We will be using an online system called Educere for credit recovery. While most of the work can be done online, attendance is mandatory three days a week via zoom. Dates: July 13th-31st. Students must be 16 years of age or older to enroll. Students will have the opportunity to make up 1 credit. Every student works at a different pace and every course has a different rigor. The credit is earned once the course is complete.

Interested in enrolling? Please reach out to Mrs. Wagener: 320-358-1267 or jwagener@rushcity.k12.mn.us

post_text:
Closure of Rush City Aquatic Center for 2020 Season

On Tuesday, May 12th, the Rush City School Board voted to close the Rush City Aquatic Center for
the summer of 2020. This tough decision was driven by operational obstacles, guidance obtained
from the Minnesota Department of Health (MDH) and the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention
(CDC). The ability to comply with proper social distancing and additional safety recommendations
would be extremely difficult and prohibits the Rush City School District and City of Rush City from
ensuring the safety of our guests and our staff.
We know how much the community and surrounding area values the Rush City Aquatic Center, and
this decision to close comes only after exhausting every effort. This closure includes the park for daily
attendance along with all classes, birthday parties, and private rentals.
Season pass holders will automatically be provided a full refund. The Rush City Aquatic Center plans
to reopen in 2021.

We know how much the community and surrounding area values the Rush City Aquatic Center, and
this decision to close comes only after exhausting every effort. This closure includes the park for daily
attendance along with all classes, birthday parties, and private rentals.
Season pass holders will automatically be provided a full refund. The Rush City Aquatic Center plans
to reopen in 2021.

!!!Important Information!!!

In accordance with the Stay At Home Order issued by Governor Walz and Minnesota executive order, Rush City School Districts will be taking the following actions:

1. Playground facilities are closed until further notice. This includes basketball courts, football fields, and baseball fields.

2. Buildings will be closed until further notice and staff will be working remotely. Should you need to reach someone at either schools or the district office please feel free to contact them at the number below and we will be happy to assist you.

JACOBSON ELEMENTARY-320-358-4274
HIGH SCHOOL-320-358-4795
DISTRICT OFFICE-320-358-4855

We apologize for any inconvenience, however, we are taking all measures to ensure proper safety.

shared_text:
Rush City School District #139
March 25 at 8:12 PM ·

Seniors! Seniors!

A message from Mrs. Wagener...

"These last couple of weeks have been crazy but I sure am proud of all of you. So many questions asked and applications already turned in. I will be available on March 31st from 10am-4:30pm for you to drop off your scholarship packets. Please pull up to the front office doors and I will come collect them. If I am not outside please call 320-358-1267. You will not be allowed in the building and we need to social distance. Please make sure you are triple checking that you have everything . I know The Womens Club Scholarship needs my signaute and I will go through and sign them all.

If this time doesn't work please reach out to me ASAP so we can plan something together.

If your applications are completed now, please let me know and we can plan for early drop off.

As always please let me know if you have any questions or concerns,
--- Mrs. Wagener---

P.S. miss you all!"

Heat or Food? - - - You do not have to choose- - -

Too many low-income Minnesotans have to choose between paying their energy bill and other necessities - food, medicine, and healthcare. Minnesota’s Energy Assistance Program offers eligible residents help to pay their energy bills so they
do not have to choose between life’s necessities. Spread the word to your friends and family.

https://mn.gov/commerce/eap.jsp

post_text: Want to go watch the the section final hockey game on Thursday night? We will try to get a fan bus filled up to head down to the game. The Dragons play at 7:00 pm at Fogerty Arena in Blaine. The fan bus will leave at 5:00 pm from the front of the high school and return right after the game. Total Tiger Wellness 2020

Thank you for your support of Community Education!

Due to unforeseen circumstances there was a delay in mailing out our spring/winter offerings: Hopefully you have recently received this mailing or will receive it in the next 24 hours! You will notice that the registration form states the deadline for registration as Friday, February 28. Because of this delay, we are extending the registration deadline to be postmarked/received by Wednesday March 4.

You may mail in your registration or choose to drop it off at the Rush City High School office. While pre-registration is preferred, if you are unable to pre-register most classes will accept registration on the first day.

See the link below for printable versions of the mailer and registration form on the Rush City Community Education Website:
https://www.rushcity.k12.mn.us/community/community_education

shared_text:
Chisago County Sheriff's Office is at C.E. Jacobson Elementary.
February 12 at 3:53 PM · Rush City, MN ·

Our Rush City School Resource Officer just graduated from the DARE Instructor Training Program! Deputy Jessica Gage graduated with 25 other law enforcement officers last week.

She will begin working with students at C.E. Jacobson Elementary School in the 2020-21 school year. She's also looking into the possibility of expanding this to the middle school and high school. Through the DARE program students will learn how to make smart and healthy choices.

Chief Deputy Wood is pictured here alongside Deputy Gage. Also in this picture is a close friend and mentor, Terri. Jessica met Terri back when she was in school, and Terri served as her DARE Instructor!

post_text: Governor Walz has declared this week as Minnesota School Counseling Week! "School Counselors: Helping Build Better Humans," to focus public attention on the unique contribution of school counselors within U.S. school systems. National School Counseling Week, sponsored by ASCA, highlights the tremendous impact school counselors can have in helping students achieve school success and plan for a career. National School Counseling Week is always celebrated the first full week in February.

post_text: We have had three special guest speakers in FACS this month. Maureen Sybrant, former kindergarten teacher, spoke to our Child Development class about the development of the 5 year old brain and learning milestones. Troy Schmeling, Meat and Seafood Director for Kowalski's grocery stores, spoke to our food preparation class about the sustainability of our seafood and certified organic meats. Finally, Ilene Olson came and spoke about jobs. She told us about her career in and around Home Ec and Early Childhood Education and discussed future student plans including the Fransden scholarship opportunities.
